defaultCrime Scene – 
defaultA review of police crime and incident reports,
default HMIC, London, January 2012, para 2.4.
default When a crime has been recorded, it can only be declassified (which is referred to as ‘no-crimed’) if the strict criteria set out in the HOCR apply. No-crimes account for approximately 3-4% of overall recorded crime. No-criming is an important part of the 
defaultHOCR as it caters for situations where the original decision to record a crime clearly turns out to be wrong (for example, where someone reports to the police that their car has been stolen from a multi-storey car park, only to find it later on a different
default floor). While it is appropriate for some cases to be no-crimed, when this is done incorrectly it can mean that suspects may not be brought to justice and the force’s published crime figures will be inaccurate.
